	<annotation>
		<!-- Marginalia -->
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Elementa artium norunt multi: quintam essentiam nemo. 
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Many know the elements of the arts, yet no one knows the quintessence.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Antippo">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Temporis Censura Optima.
						Veritas, Temporis filia. Viua vox, parasitam agit.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Temporis Censura"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nam
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Antippus, rara auis in terris.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Antippus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				An excellent judgment of time.
				Truth is the daughter of time. The living voice only makes a parasite. 
				Indeed, Antippus is a person of rarity in the world.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sensi Aschami Germanicum discursum; cum Heiuodi Prouerbijs, et Epigrammatis;
						infinitam discurrendi, arguendiq[ue] facultatem suppeditare quibusdam generosis,
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Roger Ascham"/>
					<person name="John Heywood"/>
					<book title="Report and Discourse"/>
					<book title="The Proverbs, Epigrams, and Miscellanies of John Heywood"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Aschami Germanicum discursum"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Prouerbijs"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Epigrammatis"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="infinitam discurrendi"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="facultatem suppeditare"/>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Jus commune profitentibus.
						Vnus eorum addebat Chaloneri Moria[e] Encomiu[m]:
						et videbatur singularis.
						Sed erat egregi&egrave; promptus, et
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Thomas Chaloner"/>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						fluens. Et nihil putabat elegantius, aut argutius suo Aschamo, Chalonero, Heiuodo.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				I heard the Germanic discourse of Ascham; with Heywood's Proverbs and Epigrams;
				that endless faculty of discussing and declaring to furnish with something noble, with something professing common law. 
				Someone added Chaloner's In Praise of Folly: and it was seen as singular.
				But he was exceptionally quick and fluent.
				And he thought nothing more elegant and more clever than his Ascham, Chaloner, and Heywood.
					<!-- CG: Translation unclear. Specialist help required! -->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
